</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">THE NEWS<br /><span style="font-size:12px;text-transform:uppercase;font-weight:normal;"><em>The latest from The Sun</em></span></h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">POLITICS</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/10/colorado-house-democrats-open-meetings-lawsuit/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Two Colorado House Democrats sue their caucus, Republicans for alleged violations of open meetings laws</h2>

<p>Democratic Reps. <strong>Elisabeth Epps</strong> of Denver and <strong>Bob Marshall </strong>of Highlands Ranch filed a lawsuit in Denver District Court against their party caucus alleging &#8220;pervasive&#8221; violations of state open meeting laws, including unrecorded mandatory meetings and the use of the encrypted messaging service Signal to discuss voting and witness testimony. <strong>Jesse Paul</strong>, <strong>Elliott Wenzler</strong> and <strong>Sandra Fish</strong> dig deeper into the intraparty spat â€” and the latest volley in the battle over open meetings. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/10/colorado-house-democrats-open-meetings-lawsuit/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>STORY</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">HOUSING</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/tiny-home-rules-veterans-housing-colorado/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Tiny homes starting to be a big-deal solution for people priced out of Colorado&#8217;s housing market</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/VCP-Village_tiny-homes___JS_9.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/tiny-home-rules-veterans-housing-colorado/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Tiny houses approach completion June 16 at VCP Village in Longmont. (Jeremy Sparig, Special to The Colorado Sun)</em></span></p>

<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="width:90%;max-width:500px;border-left: 4px double #fcd232;padding: 0px 10px;padding: 0px 10px;margin-left:0;"><span style="font-size:1.2em;line-height:1.3em;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-weight:bold;">&#8220;The new law outlines building codes for counties to use on tiny homes and gives those governments a way to allow people to live in them permanently. It&#8217;s just another option for people who otherwise can&#8217;t afford a standard home.&#8221;</span><br><br><span style="font-size:1em;"><em>â€” Art Laubach of Einstyne Tiny Homes in Brighton</em></span></blockquote>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">400 square feet</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">The maximum size of structure considered a &#8220;tiny home&#8221; under new state law.</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>Despite being the focus of multiple television shows and dozens of neighborhood-level political battles over the past decade or so, there haven&#8217;t been any official building codes or standards for tiny homes in Colorado. That lack of regulation meant that in many parts of the state, living permanently in a small structure was against the law. But as <strong>Monte Whaley </strong>reports, <strong>House Bill 1242</strong>, which sets building standards for the scaled-down structures and went into effect July 1, could unleash a whole new crop of permanent tiny homes in places that are the hardest hit by the housing crisis. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/tiny-home-rules-veterans-housing-colorado/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>STORY</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">ENERGY</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/xcel-energy-electric-rate-hike-colorado/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Xcel Energy seeks $45M rate increase â€” down from $312M â€” amid consumer outrage over rising bills</h2>

</mj-text>
<mj-table>
	<tr style="border:2px solid white;">
	<td style="padding: 6px;text-align:center;font-size:22px;background-color:#fcd232;font-weight:bold;" width="40%">$1.54</td><td style="font-size:14px;padding:12px;color:#000000;background-color:#DCEEF2;" width="60%">The monthly amount that the new rate increase sought by Xcel would add to the average home&#8217;s energy bill.</td></tr>
</mj-table>
<mj-text>

<p>Back in November, <strong>Xcel Energy</strong> filed a rate increase request with the <strong>Public Utilities Commission</strong> for a whopping $312 million â€” calculated by a controversial &#8220;future test year&#8221; model and a guaranteed 10.5% return on the company&#8217;s investment. Since then, a coalition of regulators, consumer advocates, municipal governments and businesses fought the increase request and negotiated it down to the current request of $45 million. <strong>Mark Jaffe</strong> has much more on the request â€” and how you can participate in the next public hearings. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/xcel-energy-electric-rate-hike-colorado/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>STORY</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">CLIMATE</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/colorado-gas-lawn-equipment-ban-ozone/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Front Range inches closer to banning gas-powered mowers and blowers in fight against ozone pollution</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/TruckAir_HC_02.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/colorado-gas-lawn-equipment-ban-ozone/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Downtown Denver under hazy air photographed April 21, 2022. (Hugh Carey, The Colorado Sun)</em></span></p>

<p>It&#8217;s looking likely that state air pollution regulators will vote to ban the sale of gas-powered mowers, blowers, edgers and other hand-held lawn equipment in the nine Front Range counties with the most concentrated ozone problems. <strong>Michael Booth</strong> has more on how the ban is shaping up, including a gradual phase-out of using existing gas-powered equipment for institutional and commercial users. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/11/colorado-gas-lawn-equipment-ban-ozone/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>STORY</strong></a></p>

&nbsp;<hr />&nbsp;

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">OUTDOORS</h4>

<h2 style="padding-bottom:0;margin-bottom:0;"><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/10/colorado-pilot-grand-teton-helicopter-landing/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" style="text-decoration:none;color:#003D5A;">Colorado pilot cited for landing helicopter in Grand Teton National Park</h2>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/helicopter-tetons-7-10-23.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/10/colorado-pilot-grand-teton-helicopter-landing/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Photo of Peter Smith's helicopter in Grand Teton National Park on June 24. (Provided by Grand Teton National Park)</em></span></p>

<blockquote class="wp-block-quote" style="width:90%;max-width:500px;border-left: 4px double #fcd232;padding: 0px 10px;padding: 0px 10px;margin-left:0;"><span style="font-size:1.2em;line-height:1.3em;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-weight:bold;">&#8220;All of these articles are coming up saying we had a picnic â€” there was no picnic.&#8221;</span><br><br><span style="font-size:1em;"><em>â€” Peter Smith, the owner of Gunnison-based West Elk Air</em></span></blockquote>

<p><strong>Peter Smith</strong> has been charged by the <strong>National Park Service</strong> for two instances of unauthorized landing on the shore of Jackson Lake, inside Grand Teton National Park. Smith says he landed because of an ill passenger and didn&#8217;t know he was inside the park boundaries. &gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2023/07/10/colorado-pilot-grand-teton-helicopter-landing/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email"><strong>STORY</strong></a></p>

