</mj-text><mj-text margin="0" padding="0"><h3 style="padding:.3em;font-family:'Libre Franklin','Arial Black';font-weight:700;background-color:#fcd232;font-size:24px;text-align:center;">Today&#8217;s Thing</h3></mj-text><mj-text>

<p><em>Today&#8217;s Thing is something we&#8217;ve used, bought, cooked, visited, watched, listened to or otherwise enjoyed lately. These aren&#8217;t ads, just recommendations â€” but if you want to support us, </em><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/join"><em>you can become a member</em></a><em>! Got something to share? Email </em><a target="_blank"  href="mailto:things@coloradosun.com"><em>things@coloradosun.com</em></a><em>.</em></p>

<h4 style="background-color:#003D5A;color:#ffffff;padding:.3em;">OUTDOORS</h4>

</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/zoleo2-scaled.jpg?w=800" /><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>The Zoleo is one of a number of satellite communication devices that can help you stay connected when you&#8217;re in the backcountry. This wallet-sized device costs $200 and requires a monthly subscription. (David Krause, The Colorado Sun)</em></span></p>

<p><strong>Satellite communicator.</strong> &gt;&gt; Earlier this summer my wife and I were on a 6-mile hike with some friends when I talked about coming back to this particular trailhead to do a longer, more remote hike. Now, I&#8217;ve done plenty of epic hikes and topped a half-dozen of our 14ers. But evidently something clicked in the back of my wife&#8217;s mind, and about a week later a global satellite communicator showed up at the house. (Perhaps the fact that I&#8217;m in my mid-50s, got lucky to beat the &#8220;widowmaker&#8221; heart attack last year and have been fighting bad knees for decades had something to do with her purchase. Just guessing.)</p>

<p>Then I got to thinking: I don&#8217;t have to take this just when I want to challenge myself with an all-day hike. I can take it whenever we&#8217;re out visiting the places where we don&#8217;t have cell service when we&#8217;re rafting or snowboarding or jeeping. And, heck, it&#8217;s not just for me. It is a great tool to help someone else we might come across if they&#8217;re in trouble in a remote area.</p>

<p>So with 14ers season in full swing, I encourage you to check out some of the satellite comm options. Amy bought me the wallet-sized Zoleo, which at $200 is on the moderate end of the price scale. The most important feature is it can send an SOS from anywhere on Earth, but it can also send a &#8220;check-in&#8221; signal as well as text messages and get weather updates. When cell or Wi-Fi coverage isn&#8217;t an option, messages are transmitted over the Iridium satellite network, which is the most expansive system circling the globe.</p>

<p>Heads up, you&#8217;re likely going to have to download the app that corresponds with the device and you also have a monthly service fee (I went with the $20/month option) to get that satellite connection. After 30 years, I guess her wanting me to come home from each adventure means she still likes me! &gt;&gt;<strong> </strong><a target="_blank"  href="https://www.zoleo.com/en-us/satellite-communicator"><strong>Zoleo</strong></a><strong>, </strong><a target="_blank"  href="https://www.rei.com/search?q=satellite+messengers"><strong>REI</strong></a></p>

